Runs a cross-language differential test: compiles javelin-ext's C++ dictionary against upstream javelin-steno, replays every golden stroke sequence through it, and verifies the output matches the Rust reference walker's recorded verdicts. This is the only place the generated dictionary (built by build-javelin and written to out/) is actually executed.

Missing C++ toolchain or upstream javelin-steno tree exits with SKIP, not FAIL — the Rust unit/integration tests in crates/steno/tests/infinite.rs already fully pin the walker's logic, so absence of a host compiler is not a coverage gap. Missing generated headers (out/steno_generated_dictionary_data.h, out/steno_generated_testdata.h) is a FAIL, since the caller (crates/steno/tests/cpp_check.rs) is contractually obligated to have run build-javelin first.

The data header must not contain enumerated nested answers like "Array<Array<number>>" — only type markers like "Array<%t>". If such a string appears, nesting was pre-expanded instead of walked, defeating the whole point; the check catches this anti-cheat violation before compilation.

Compiles a minimal curated link set from javelin-steno (stroke.cc, str.cc, dictionary.cc, crc32.cc, list.cc) — full javelin does not host-compile — and links against steno_generated_dictionary.cc and test_main.cc from javelin-ext. The define JAVELIN_EXT_RUN_TESTS activates the differential test's main(); javelin's own RUN_TESTS is not used. The script does not invoke cargo (would deadlock on target lock when called from within `cargo test`); the caller has already written the headers.